      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "CAUTION! The problem with just applying some rounding mode is that it also has effect on operations that would normally return a value having a finite number of decimal places. When rounding is used the result is scaled to the scale of a divident.   For example: 1 / 8 will result in 0.125 but if you apply rounding it will be 1."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 173186,
        "reputation" : 4709,
        "user_id" : 401712,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8ab83e913223d2bee3eb4c4b5629122a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Dario Seidl",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/401712/dario-seidl"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1715619489,
      "post_id" : 4591216,
      "comment_id" : 138346171,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "To clarify the difference between precision and scale: The precision is the maximum number of digits used for operators, scale is the number of digits right to the decimal point. A <code>MathContext</code> has precision, a <code>BigDecimal</code> has a scale. Typical values for precision are 7 (decimal32) or 16 (decimal64). Whereas, you use scale 2 when you want a rounded result with 2 decimal places, like 0.17."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 41067,
      "reputation" : 130053,
      "user_id" : 119280,
